observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the management:
Direct the Local Finance Committee to develop reasonable budget estimates for subsequent fiscal years, minimizing discrepancies between estimated and actual income, and ensuring sufficient funds for government project implementation;
Require the Local Finance Committee to implement a systematic and realistic revenue forecasting process, incorporating historical data and statistical analysis;
Direct the Local Finance Committee to review the current budgeting process under the City Budget Office, providing clear guidance to revenue-generating departments for target attainment; and
Require the City Treasurer and revenue-generating departments to conduct periodic reviews of collection performance, analyze collection shortfalls, and implement corrective measures to prevent future deficits.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Treasurer to:
Exhaust all remedies for RPT collection as outlined in R.A. No. 7160;
Immediately issue demand letters to all delinquent taxpayers;
Implement a comprehensive information campaign to educate real property owners about their tax obligations, available discounts for early payment, and the potential consequences of non-compliance, including property seizure; and
Provide a documented plan of action to address and resolve all outstanding delinquencies within the prescriptive period.

We recommended that the Management:

Direct the Local Finance Committee to reasonably estimate budget for the succeeding calendar years to avoid significant difference from actual income collectible and never compromise the implementation of government projects with the insufficiency of funds caused by the low income collection;

Require the Local Finance Committee to make a systematic and realistic forecasting of revenue taking into account prior years’ experience and statistics as aids in setting targets;

Direct the Local Finance Committee to undertake a review of the present budgeting done under the stewardship of the City Budget Office to set a clearer guide for the concerned revenue generating Departments toward attaining the targets set; and

Require the City Treasurer and other Departments involved in generating revenues to meet its targets by conducting periodic review of collection performance by the concerned officials to ascertain whether collection targets are attained; and to analyze the reasons for the shortfall in collections and find alternative solution to minimize, reduce or avoid incurrence of shortfall in the future.

We recommended the    Management to:

immediately conduct appraisal of all its land by hiring an independent and qualified appraiser or expert as required under COA Resolution No. 89-17;

adjust the carrying amounts of the affected assets in the City’s books once the results of the appraisal are obtained in accordance with Items 44, 54-56 of IPSAS 17;

update the data for the difference in the List of Land Account of the City Accountant to conform with the Real Property Tax Declaration of the City Assessor; and

adjust and drop from the City’s Books the unrecorded lot and the double recorded lots, respectively.

Based on the above observations, we recommended to the Management the following:

Through the City Accountant (i) prepare subsidiary ledgers that would completely account for each item of PPE in the financial statements; (ii) provide a full and appropriate disclosure of the PPE Account in the Notes to Financial Statements as prescribed in the NGAS and IPSAS 17;

Establish an Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory count on all PPE items owned by the City and reconcile the results against the recorded amounts maintained by the Accounting Office; adjust the Property, Plant and Equipment Accounts in the books as necessary; prepare and submit the corresponding report together with the established subsidiary ledger for each class of PPE;

Facilitate the immediate disposal of the unserviceable properties in order to realize gain from sale thereof and to be derecognized from the accounting records; and

Complete and submit the Inventory of all Local Roads and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Cards, Report on Local Road Network of the City as shown in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2015-008. The preparation of the Report of Local Road Network must be observed yearly. Also, keep and maintain the Local Road Network Property/Property Ledger Card for all roads and its components.

We recommended to Management the following courses of action:
All department heads concerned are enjoined to monitor the implementation of all projects funded by other national government agencies, particularly those programs and activities relating to their offices in order to achieve the ultimate goals and objectives of the fund which is to promote general welfare and provide basic services to the constituents;

Require the City Accountant and City Treasurer to update and reconcile the balances in their books and prepare the utilization reports for the implemented projects duly approved by the Local Chief Executive in order to establish the correct balance of the Due to NGAs account in the financial statements of the City Government;

Immediately return to the Source Agencies the unused/unutilized balance of P0.598 million relating to the fund transfers;

The City Accountant should draw the adjusting journal entries to properly recognize Due from Other Funds - General Fund on the counterpart of the LGU to the project amounting to P0.319 million that was charged to the Trust Fund. Likewise, recognize Due to Other Funds in the Trust Fund books for the amount of P1.000 million from DOH for COVID assistance that was charged under General Fund. Also, the collections amounting to P2,275.07 should be categorized as Permit Fees in the General Fund books instead of Due to NGAs in the Trust Fund books and the long outstanding balances totaling P11,293.14 should also be recorded as Trust Liabilities in the General Fund books; and

The City Treasurer should deposit all receipts of fund transfers from national government agencies in the corresponding trust bank accounts and the City Accountant should record the same in the Trust Fund books. Accordingly, all trust funds should be used only for the purposes for which the funds were received.

We enjoined Management through the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to submit the following lacking documents in order to support Management’s observance with all the rules and regulations and directives issued with regard to procurements during the state of public health emergency:
Evidence of posting of Purchase Orders in the agency website or any conspicuous place in the premise of the Procuring Entity and the GPPB online portal for Emergency Procurement;
Evidence of posting of updated APP in the GPPB online portal;
Mayor’s or Business Permit of the suppliers;
Income Tax Returns (Annual Income Tax Return of the preceding tax year or Business Tax Returns (Value Added Tax or Percentage Tax Return covering the previous six months) of the suppliers; and
Omnibus Sworn Statement (OSS), which shall be an original copy, of the suppliers.
We also recommended that Management through the City Accountant ensure that disbursement vouchers together with the supporting documents are properly and completely accomplished and authorized as prescribed under Section 4, paragraphs 5 and 6 of P.D. 1445.

We strictly recommended and reiterated that Management and its Local Finance Committee undertake an immediate review of the financial condition of the City Government and identify areas and propose control mechanisms to ease the cash deficit such as but not limited to the following:
Deferment of the programs, projects and activities programmed from the unrealized revenues during the year should be reviewed and reconsidered;
All unused balances of appropriations without reinforced cash should not be obligated at year-end;
Expenditures should be limited to the amount of available actual revenues during the year; controllable expenses should be minimized considering that actual revenue collections during the year was deficient against the projected/targeted amounts; and
Accelerate local tax collection measures.
Additionally, strictly stop the practice of using trust funds for payment of regular expenditures to avoid the incurrence of cash overdraft.

We recommended that Management submit the following lacking documents:
Duly certified and duly-received distribution list with signatures of recipients;
Original copies of Official Receipts;
Memorandum of Agreement with source agency;
Revised Annual Procurement Plan;
Evidence of posting of Purchase Order in the agency website or any conspicuous place in the premise of the Procuring Entity and the GPPB online portal for Emergency Procurement;
Evidence of posting of updated APP in the GPPB online portal;
Mayor’s or Business Permit of the supplier;
Income Tax Returns (Annual Income Tax Return of the preceding tax year or Business Tax Returns (Value Added Tax or Percentage Tax Return covering the previous six months) of the supplier; and
Omnibus Sworn Statement (OSS), notarized, which shall be an original copy, of the supplier.
